segments.text: Colonel Frank G. This is a test, this is a test.
This is an interview with Colonel Frank G. Anderson, head coach, Texas A&M Track, 1922 to 1935, 1946 to 1957, and Commandant of the Corps of Cadets, 1935 to 1937.
This is a test.
This is the 26th of July, 1983.
This is Terry Anderson.
26th of July, 1983.
This is a test.
So can we start there?
Yes.
Okay, this is an interview with Frank G. Anderson at his home and college station.
And we are going to start off talking about how you got to A&M.
I know it dealt with Mr. Bibles.
Are we ready?
Yeah.
Before we talk about A&M, I would like to include the name of D.X.
Bob in my past history.
He was my prep school coach back in Tennessee at Brandon Training School.
I graduated
from White County High School up at Sparta, Tennessee.
I made a good many touchdowns.
Two touchdowns was against a school named Fitzgerald Clark.
And at that time, it was a young coach beginning his career there.
And I scored four touchdowns against his team.
Right over in the adjoining county there was another young coach having his first year at Shelbyville, Tennessee.
They played each other.
I made enough touchdowns against this team, this prep school team, Fitzgerald and Clark, at Tallahoma.
I made four touchdowns playing on the White County High School team.
I didn't have any money to go to college.
I was offered a $40 job as freight clerk in the depot.
at the end of a branch line on the railway.
But then, thank goodness, a boy, the son of the headmaster at Brandon Training School, the son came up there and recruited me to go an extra year in prep school.

I didn't, as I say, I had very few prospects of ever going to college, and so I thought maybe if I went down there and did pretty well, maybe somebody would offer me a scholarship or help me get a job to have a scholarship.
So I went down there, and then this young coach down there in his first year, D. X. Bible,
was just a fine young man.
He was a good Christian man, Baptist Church, and he taught a Sunday school class at Shelbyville.
And it just so happened that the
preacher at this Baptist church, happened to be a graduate from Mississippi College, which is kind of the Baylor of Mississippi, and they were looking for a coach.
And Coach Bible did real well, and I did pretty well, too, I guess, because he says, boy, you're going to college with me.
So I went to college with DX Bible down there and we had a very fine year.
He stayed there three years and he did so well that the people out at A&M heard about him and they gave him a job.
He came over here and he did real well for two or three years.
His team's already been scored on.
Both he and I, though, went into World War I, and when the World War I was over, I had finished my time at Mississippi College.
We had won the state championship.
We had beaten Tulane.
We had scored on Alabama.
And we beat Mississippi State, and we never did lose the University of Mississippi.
One time we beat that team 74 to 7, where you believe it or not, we did it.
And so, D.X.
then, he was just getting started over here, and he had just been here before the war as a freshman coach, I guess.
Maybe one year more than that.
But he wasn't athletic director until one year after the war was over.
I went back to Mississippi College after the war was over.
I'm now a major in the Army.
I happened to go in there as a captain.
I guess I was the only captain in World War I that had never had a uniform on or saluted anybody.
But he offered me a position.
He said, you go on coach at Mississippi College one year and then come on out there and be my freshman coach.
Now I have
covered that tile up to explain how I got here and who brought me here.
That was my best friend in the world, the ex-bible.
Can you describe the type of person?
Can you describe what
type of person Bible was?
Would you describe him?

Oh, as I said, he was a fine enough character back in Shelbyville, Tennessee that that preacher at that Baptist school where he taught that Sunday school class recommended him in every way to go and said, you better hire the man.
He went down there and he impressed them and they offered him the job.
He stayed with that job for three years.
Could you tell me a little bit about World War I, your experience in World War I?
Well, Mississippi College furnished a rifle company to the Confederacy.
When World War I broke out,
they wanted a unit into the army.
And this good old patriotic president just, he just practically got us all to, who were at least wanted to, enough to form a battery of field artillery.
These boys elected their own captain.
They elected me captain.
And the reason they elected me captain, I had scored lots of touchdowns in football.
I happened to be a class president.
over there and I might have made a mistake in leaving Mississippi because if I stayed there I believe I could have been elected to the governor of the state.
Later on one of the boys I coached was elected to the governor of the state and that over there.
Now the war is over.
Where did you go in the war?
Did you go to Europe?
Oh yes, I was in the artillery, he was in the air force.
And we were over there a year.
You were in France?
In France, yes.
Okay, can we stop just for a minute?
Okay.
Now let's continue as soon as the war is over.
DX had a little...
summer get-together, his sister and a friend, a girl from Texas, he and I were at a little summer resort for a few days and he offered me the job to come out here.
But he says, I can't, I'm not in charge for one year.
After one year, the man who's on the job will be gone and I'll have his place.
And so I took that job for a year
and then I came out here as his freshman coach in 1920.
Now, Mississippi College had never, had never scored on Mississippi State or University of Mississippi or Alabama or Tulane or those teams.
We played them a warm-up game for them, always, but by golly,
The first year we played Ole Miss, it was a 7-7 tie.
The next year, we just mercilessly slaughtered them, as I've told you.
The score was 74-7.
Then we went right on down, and I just happened to make an 80-yard run against Mississippi State.
That game up there, his first game and my first game in football, I guess something happened that had never happened in a football game.
We led Mississippi State up on their campus at the end of the half, 14 to nothing.
But we had gone up there with 14 players.
We didn't have a big squad.
But he had only a guarantee of $250 and he had to clear a little money, so he goes up there with
with 12 men.
No, with 14 men.
That's right, he had 14 men.
And when you play both ways, offensive and defensive, against a big squad, you're in pretty good shape after that first half is over with.
And so with five minutes to play,
They were leading us 14 to 13, and we didn't have 11 men that could stand up.
And so we just go out of this other team and said, Du Bois, you know we can't play you anymore.
You're ahead of us now.
Let's quit.
They said, all right, we'll just quit.
And we went over and told the coaches that we had decided to call the game off.
And they were winning 14 to 13.
And that's the only time that ever happened to them.
history of college football on without a doubt.
Well then, next week we go down to Tulane.
There's a young coach down there by the name of Shaughnessy.
He and Dix had all gone up to see old Doc Williams
up at Minnesota.
He was a famous old coach.
He was having a coaching school.
Well these two young freshman college coaches, both getting ready to go to be a college coach this coming year.
One of them was going to coach at Tulane, the other one was going to coach at Mississippi College.
They were going to meet each other, so they put up a bet that when the game was over in New Orleans that fall, that the loser would pay for the supper.
All right, we go down there.
Now I don't know, we had already played Mississippi State a 14-13 game.
I guess that's the only part that got in.
But this young coach down there, Shaughnessy, decided that since he's playing a team that never had done anything in the past,
except just fill in a date for a warm-up game.
He'd just go up to LSU and scout LSU, turn the game over to his captain.
Well, the poor guy was pretty badly shocked when he came home and found his team was beat.
Well, I just happened to make a run there in that game that the people put it in the paper.
We beat them.
We beat Kool-Aid.
And of course next year the guy stayed at home when we played him.
We went down and beat him again.
So that's the way things went.
So D. X.
Bottle got a job out here on account of his record over there with a school that had never done anything.
Now, Bible's record here was outstanding.
And I was wondering why it was so good.
What were some of the things that he taught his men?
I mean, there were years in which no one scored on his team.
Or no one scored against him.
For two or three years.
Yes, I was wondering why was he so good?
Did you know that his teams usually won seven to nothing or fourteen or nothing or fourteen or something?
Yeah.
He never scored any scores much.
He had a fine defense and some fine kickers.
And he just beat them that way.
He beat them on defense then.
Yeah.
Now we're going to come back to A&M and A&M Athletics.
OK. DX's record was good.
But DX did not believe in giving anybody one cent to come to play on his team.
James Sullivan was more interested in bricks than he was in equipment or anything else.
He wanted to build a stadium.
Between the two of them, they built a stadium.
But between the two of them, they ran completely out of material.
Lusher Stark, a rich old man, was taking care of Texas with some help from some other people.
The Dallas businessmen were taking care of SMU.
The Rice people, certainly Rice is a fine great team, and I'm not besmirching them any whatsoever.
But Houston probably helped them out too, you see.
And here we sat with not giving anybody anything.
Party X ran out of a team.
He saw the handwriting on the wall and he left A&M.
He put them up and then he let them slide down, but he let them slide down because he was honestly an amateur.
He hadn't been used to, he helped me out.

He helped me out, but after one year he didn't have to help me out much because I told those people, get me that laundry job and let me pick up the dirty shirts and collars and I'll make my way in there.
That's the kind of a scholarship I had over there that first year.
Well, so much for that.
So much for that.
Now,
I've lost my line.
Okay.
I'd like to...
find out about when you became the head track coach in 1922.
How did that happen?
You came over here in 1920 to be the freshman baseball, basketball and track coach and then in 1922 you became the head coach.
I haven't told you about Charlie Cummings and the first thing that they gave us, first job.
I would just like to explain
why I have tried to explain why A&M didn't do too well in his latter years, but when he left here and went to Nebraska, good old Matty Bale came here as his successor.
But Matty didn't have anything.
He actually let things run out to nothing, just going down to where we couldn't play a decent,
Much more than a decent high school team almost.
But Matty Bell had... Why did DX let this happen?
Because he wouldn't give anybody a dollar to come here.
No scholarships.
Everybody out was bringing them in and he wasn't bringing them in.
He didn't want to bring them in.
Why didn't he want to?
Because he was an amateur.
He believed that...
He believed that...
We shouldn't hire athletes.
But when he left here to go to Nebraska, he realized that he either had to quit coaching or do what the others were doing.
He went to Nebraska when they were down, but he got all he could get at Nebraska.
And he built a team up there.
that was a champion.

Texas heard about him, knew about him, they knew about what he had done to them in the earlier years here and they hired him to come back to Texas and they were on the very bottom and he helped them back up.
And now we'll just have to say thank you to good old DX and go on from there and take up Matty Bell.
When Matty came here,
He had very, very little talent.
He had a little old backfield.
I don't think any of them were bigger than I am.
And I weighed about 140.
And they were slow.
And of course he couldn't do any good.
He didn't do any good.
After about three years, they fired Matty.
The first man under a scholarship when he came down here was a boy by the name of Charlie Cummings.
He was a brown boy and a very fine football player.
He came out here, now Matty,
is on the job.
But DX and Sully had got together and they promised the boy if he'd come out here, they would pay him $25 to sweep out to our field house.
That's the first money that A&M ever paid for an athlete.
What year was that?
That was in the year of, it was Matty Bell's first year.
I would say it was, say, 33.
Just as a guess, I'd say that's what it was.
Poor old Charlie got ineligible.
He didn't pass his work and he lost his job and he lost his $25.
Isn't that something?
Yeah, that's too bad.
That's all the money was spent when Matty Bill's first year was $25 on Charlie Cummings and he didn't make the grade.
He didn't ever help us in it.
Matty didn't have a chance.
And they fired that man without even talking to him.
He read it in the paper that he was fired.
I loved old Matty Bell.
Why?
Because he was such a fine fella.
He was a crackerjack coach because he had beaten the heck out of us a number of years before we brought him down here.
That's when we hired him.
But if you don't win, you don't last.
Yeah.
Now, next year up at SMU, you know what he did?
Went to the Rose Bowl.
That just shows us up.
That showed up the people who are running things down here.
Farmer students have got no business running outfits.
Listen, as track coach, I have never asked a former student to give me a dollar for track.
I've had Charlie Babcock and Jimmy Williams who worked for Tyree Bell at Dallas helped me land the first two boys I ever gave scholarships to.
Not the first two, I gave a scholarship to another one before I did them.
Those two boys helped me win championships.
We wouldn't have won championships without those two boys.
But I gave only six full-time scholarships in all of my time here.
And I coached 13 years after they started giving scholarships.
We wouldn't have won without those people.
We never would have won a championship without those six boys.
But I never had over
Two of them might have been on the same team at one time, but they made the difference.
But the others were made by boys who had never won first places in a conference in the Texas meet.
The first athlete I ever had, I've been out of coaching now,
for a 12 year interval.
I come back to coaching.
After the war was over I had that first interval.
I didn't do too well because of the life in A&M College.
They drove off more freshmen than they kept in some outfits.
My boys were
The boys that I would have recruited if I'd had any money to recruit or try to talk into coming here didn't come in most cases because they heard how rough and tough A&M College was.
And those that did come, some of them got run off.
Because of hazing?
On account of hazing, yes.
A&M was a fraternity.
As long as it was just a military school, it was a fraternity.
That fraternity had lasted 12 years, one full year.
Some kids couldn't take it.
We have had people start in with 35 freshmen and end up with 10.
I couldn't win with this school.
against other schools who are now going out and giving track men scholarships.
I wouldn't have taken the job, I don't think it's common then, if we'd had a chance at the boys.
But upperclassmen would respect the football freshmen.
But a poor track freshman.
What the heck with track?
That's no sport.

They'd just give him just like they would any other freshman and here's a boy that was good enough to win a mile back there and he's up here, he wants some good for nothing sophomore paddling him or doing what they want to do with him.
Well, they just won't take it.
The sons of these people who were my first years out here didn't come when their daddies talked about A&M College and what they had to go through.
Rough stuff, real stuff, Texas A&M.
That was their yell and that was their life.
Let's talk about those years when you were the first, during the 1920s.
Tell me about during the 1920s.
Now we'll go into what you, from 1920 on.
We didn't- How did you become the head track coach?
In 1921, I came out here in 20, in the spring of 21, I was assistant track coach.
But back in high school, I was the champion pole vaulter of the state of Tennessee in 1912.
And I was a good sprinter.
They, uh,
Oh, to heck, where am I?
How did you become the head track coach?
I was interested in track in other words.
Yes, yes, I know.
Rothgeb had been a track man on the University of Illinois.
He was DX's line coach.
I learned a lot of track from him.
I was a track man in high school, but I learned a lot of track from him, and I had the job after one year as his assistant in track.
What happened to him?
He stayed here for four years, and then he and somebody else went down to Rice, left us to go to Rice.
In those days now, DX was, we had three coaches.
DX was head football coach,
He also coached basketball.
Rothkopf coaches baseball.
I coach track.
So then for 12, 12 or 13 years I was, that was the setup.
When did you, when, when and how did the position of athletic director come about?
I never have been athletic director.
I know you haven't, but when did that come about?
Do you remember?
Well, they always had an athletic director here.
D.X.
was athletic director.
He was athletic director and... Matty Bell was athletic director.
Always the football coach was athletic director.
I see.
We have never had it otherwise.
And it is a rotten way to be.
Why?
A school as big as this ought to have an athletic director.
It didn't coach anything.
You can't tell me that all sports are...
equally handled if the...
I like this football coach.
I don't want to antagonize him, but I say that any big school ought to have an athletic director who coached nothing.
But he ought to have been a fine athlete.
He ought to have known athletics.
But now that's just my opinion.
That's my opinion, and a pretty strong opinion too.
but I've been able to get along with all the athletic directors here.
I got along mighty fine with Burr Bryant.
I've got a funny story to tell you about Burr.
When he came here and talking to him,
I just brought up, the subject came up and I thought he had heard about it and I said, that's the reason I resigned.
He said, you did what?
I said, well they published in the paper that when you came you could make a clean sweep of the whole deal here and I just decided I wouldn't let, I'd make it easier on you and I'd just resign.
And, which I did.
Honestly, I did.
I said, here I've stayed here all these years and I've done pretty well because we had already won six championships in those other years.
And we went and fell to third one time.
Now, so when he said, you did what?
I said, yes.
I did, but I told them at the time, I didn't want to leave.
I love it here, but by golly, I'm not going to let them fire me, so I'm resigning.
And old Bones Irvin, who was then the athletic director, said, now Frank, you know they didn't mean you.
I said, well, they said so.
They said he'd make a clean sweep, and I'm in the department.
I said, all right now, Bones, I've been here.
I've been here all these years.
I've subsidized track.
I've taken boys in my car and gone to Chicago for two of them and you give me $50 to do it.
I've taken sandwiches and gone halfway to the drug relays and going to the border Olympics and things like that and you haven't paid me anything.
I stayed here when they offered me more money to go to Rice.
Now you just go over to Texas University and find out what they're paying Clyde Littlefield.
We have beaten him six out of the last seven years.
By golly, I'm as good as he is.
You go there and find out what they're paying him, and I'll stay.
And they did it.
And I told that story to Paul Bryant.
And he says, how much they paying you?
I told him, it's not enough.
So he gave me a little raise.
Isn't that a good story?
Oh, Lordy.
Now, now.
I was wondering why you resigned from the head track coach back in 1935.
Why'd you decide to resign?
Oh, the commandant had gone.
Yeah.
I came out of World War I as a major, and in the meantime I had done
all the work necessary as an active reserve officer.
Went to camp every summer and things like that.
And I was now a full colonel.
I've got a lot of trophies back there I want you to look at before you leave.
So you worked your way up in the reserve.
Yes.
And you were a full colonel by 1935.
Yes, and so here's a man that's gone and leaving them.
And he told me that this place is going to blow up.
He did?
What was his name?
He didn't like the way things were running at A&M College.
Why?
some outfits started in with 30 and ended up with 10.
Now, well, I'm not doing as well as I want to do in track.
I don't have a good chance and the school isn't growing.
I came out here, it was 1700, now after 12 years it's just 3500.
But they're losing too many people in the freshman class.
I took that job with my eyes wide open.
I challenged the system.
I'm the first man to challenge this system.
In what way?
Tell me about it.
Well, when I first was here, I'm the brand new commandant.
We have a bonfire.
Here comes a very irate man in my office the morning after the bonfire and those damn boys carried off my log barn last night and put it on the bonfire.
I made them pay that man for that barn.
I just called the captain's end and said, you're going to pay for it.
Collect it up from your companies.
I paid the man.
And I said, you're not going to build a bonfire next year.
I'm going to build a bonfire.
And it's going to be a legal bonfire.
I took the bull ring.
The bull ring or the freshman now that didn't carry, got caught carrying you some food in the mess hall maybe.
Or anything else they want to ram a freshman for.
Of course, they didn't want to ram the freshmen for that, but old John King caught food on the freshmen and he gave them eight rams.
Now that thing right there, now there's so many other things that happened.
Why don't you continue about the legal bonfire?
Yeah, the legal bonfire.
Next year I got some saws and axes and some transportation from the building and grounds department.
And I took the bull ring.
The bull ring is composed of freshmen and maybe a few sophomores who weren't necessarily breaking college regulations but they're breaking student body regulations.
Well I took those kids out there and I got on the end of the saw just like they did.

Some up and took my turns and we cut down enough old trees and other trees between here and the airport because in those days there wasn't anything but trees on the other side of where the baseball stadium is.
And we built a bonfire of logs.
When I show you this picture in here, it's my brain child.
It's the same
It's the same thing and all we had to do that was one year and that started a new tradition and that's my tradition.
Not a bonfire but that kind of bonfire, that's my baby because we built it.
And I told these boys you're not going to be allowed to put one thing on that bonfire.
If I catch you putting the thing on that bonfire I'm going to campus you during football season next year.

Because you just, I'm just going to allow you to pill, they burned the faculty's wood piles, they burned the outhouses, they burned anything they could gather, plus what the merchants gave them, old boxes and cartons and things like that.
And they made an excellent bonfire because they caught fires so quick and burned up in the herd and weren't so darn big.
It's a shame they're burning all these good logs, I love trees.
I just had to do something about that bonfire.
Okay, what were some of the other problems that you dealt with as commandants?
They used to have a silly thing of throwing toilet paper.
Sometimes at a game they'd throw toilet paper and there was a lot of it there and I told the boys, now you've got to quit throwing that toilet paper.
And then I got him to wear the toilet paper.
And I remember this story.
Now we're first trip, court trip, going up to Fort Worth.
I got on that special car.
I'm the commandant now.
I'm the wife now.
I got the guess of the man who's running the railroad.
He's washing the car.
I got him on that thing, and I was thinking about stopping him throwing all that darn toilet paper.
And I said, I said,
I hope we don't, I just don't believe we got a lot of toilet paper on the train today.
I didn't explain to him.
And he was just shocked.
He says, I just hope we haven't overlooked that thing.
I said, oh no, no, I should have explained myself.
I said, I don't think the boys are all loaded down with toilet paper so they can throw up this football game.
Oh we managed to get rid of the toilet paper without any problem much.
The student body was pretty reasonable in that thing.
All right now but the first Friday night here they had they aired out the freshmen.
They'd get their belts and boy they had belt them as far as they could do it until they ran them clear off the campus and they don't you show up here till tomorrow.
Well I don't know.
I went along with them.
But after the next, the second year now, second year after they aired them out, I went out there and I said, now all right now boys, that's just, you got them all gone now, let's air them in.
Let's air them in.
And they cooperated with me.
We all got together and they agreed with me, fine, it's a good thing too to air them in.
And what did that mean, air them in?
Bring them back and let them sleep in their own beds.
which for years they hadn't been allowed to, first Friday night at the yellow practice, first yellow practice.

Now that's the end of the second year, but now in the second year there was one, and I was, I tried to talk them out of it, but there's one man named Frank Slacker, thank goodness, he wouldn't let his boys
He wouldn't let anybody run in one of his freshmen out of his dormitory.
He's the first.
He was a cadet?
He would not let them air out.
They didn't have to air out.
He just said it's the foolishness.
But now, also, also, the air go down here, the train comes down here.
The freshman class is down there, all of them with brooms, and they hold the train up while they sweep out the trains.
That's a fine thing for a big college to be doing, isn't it?
Somebody had to challenge this outfit.
I was having a hard time getting freshmen to come and to stay here.
I've got an opportunity now to do something about it.
And Harry Boyer said, boy, you were the toughest commandant I ever saw.
I didn't last but two years.
We had a lot of confrontations.
Now, for instance, you had to do something like this.
They tell me that I passed through the campus last night and somebody was drilling the boys at 3 o'clock.
So I go up there and find out what's going on.
Sophomore out drilling the freshman at 2 or 3 o'clock in the morning.
Well, I got out an order.
You can't do that.
You just gotta quit doing that.
But they don't pay attention to the orders you get out.
You have to enforce them.
So on the night or two, I went up there about two or three o'clock, and here was some sophomore out drilling the freshman.
I said, all right, sophomore, take these boys and put them back to bed.
You go with me.
We went to woke up the first sergeant.
All right, first sergeant, you come on and wake that damn captain up.
Asked them, why are you doing sleeping here?
The boys out drilling, some darn sophomore out drilling these boys in here, you're sleeping.
If that happens again, Bud, you're gonna get up and drill them while the freshmen sleep.
No more done.
It stops, you see, it stops.
The carrier food, now this, we're nearing the end of my second year now.
The next thing happens,
All these years I've been ramming fresh, I've been having in force rounds for freshmen for taking food out of the mess hall.
Freshmen don't need breakfast, they eat breakfast.
But they take it to some boy that wants to sleep and have something to eat.
So he makes a freshman bring him some food.
Old John King catches him and gives him eight demerits.
I send for the darn freshman and I say, freshman, I'm not gonna go ask you anything.
You'd have to lie to me.
You wouldn't dare tell me who you did that for, because that is the one percent that cannot be pardoned for in this Corps, is to squeal on an upperclassman.
But when you're a sophomore next year, doggone you, I'd be mad enough to come over here and tell me you made the freshman.
I'm not doing too much for you.
And I won't do anything for the freshman.
They don't pay attention to you.
They just go on and do it, so I have to act again.
What did you do?
Well, here's the company that one of his freshmen yesterday was turned in for, had food on him.
They're standing here ready to go to some dinner.
This captain is one of my finest friends, but he wasn't thin because I was captain
You're going to stand here until you rot or fall out or I will fall out one because you're not going to move.
You're not going to dinner today until that man steps out that made that freshman.
I've got out an order that that's going to stop and now I'm stopping it.
I'm going to find out in your outfit who made that freshman.
Take that.
I won't tell you what I'm going to do to him or what I'm going to do to him if you walk off.
